<br>
If a person is able to function in society, they know the consequences of allowing others to &quot;see&quot; the heavy depression they can carry. So they play at the game of life, until they cant anymore.<br>
<br>
Cant , doesnt mean necassarily ending ones life. It can mean not being able to get out of bed, or to do any of the simply things in life, like brush your teeth/hair, take a shower, ect.<br>
<br>
Medication can make that mood of utter failure and uselessness easier to handle. And can even keep it at bay. But not for everyone, and not a simple process of going to a doctor and getting a prescription.<br>
<br>
Clinical depression and being &quot;blue&quot; are NOT the same thing. And there are situational things that can cause almost anyone to be temperarily depressed to the clinical level. <br>
<br>
Most of us arent gong to accept that someone is so depressed they need help beyond our telling them to perk up. It is not because we dont care, rather we cant accept or wont accept that the condition is that bad. It is frightening to not be able to help someone you love and it is scary to realize the morass of deep depression can hit people.<br>
<br>
There are signs, but like anything else, they can be misread or missed. No one is an expert at decyphering depression and its many forms and moods. And active attempts to hide it can lead to not picking it up either.<br>
<br>
Initial depression is easier to spot, because the person may not be adept at hiding it yet, and of course the very deepest also, since the person may be unable to hide how they really feel.<br>
<br>
Talking to someone about depression is not fun. Most people dont want to hear it. Dont get me wrong, not in a &quot; I dont care &quot; way, rather in a &quot; I cant accept&quot; way. Kinda like talking about death and your own mortality, most people wont carry a convrsation along those lines long.<br>
<br>
Depressed people are better equiped to identify other depressed people, if they want to. Even trained professionals can only guess or surmise at what is going on. Like I have to keep reminding myself....... No one can read minds.... so when I need help, I have to ask for it, or I have to survive as best I can without any.<br>
<br>
My sister's husband is one of those morons that tells her (when she is depressed and needs medical help) ohh, just pray and God will fix it. Or he tells her she doesnt accept God or she wouldnt be depressed. Praying is GOOD, and Believing in God is too, IF you can. Anything that helps you fight is good. Dont put blinders on though. Some people need medical help, it is that simple.<br>
<br>
